03783nam a22005415i 9780226218021DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20102008ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802262180217 a10.7208/97802262180212doi  a(DE-B1597)524553  a(OCoLC)748360626  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aNA6225b.E87 2008eb 7aHIS0000002bisacsh04a725/.20973090432221 aEsperdy, Gabrielle, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aModernizing Main Street :bArchitecture and Consumer Culture in the New Deal /cGabrielle Esperdy. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2010] 4c©2008  a1 online resource (318 p.) :b66 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCenter for American Places - Center Books on American Places00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tINTRODUCTION -- t1. Main Street, U.S.A -- t2. The New Deal on Main Street -- t3. Marketing Modernization -- t4. The Architecture of Consumption -- t5. Modernism on Main Street -- t6. Conclusion: A Main Street Modernized -- tA Note on Sources -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAn important part of the New Deal, the Modernization Credit Plan helped transform urban business districts and small-town commercial strips across 1930s America, but it has since been almost completely forgotten. In Modernizing Main Street, Gabrielle Esperdy uncovers the cultural history of the hundreds of thousands of modernized storefronts that resulted from the little-known federal provision that made billions of dollars available to shop owners who wanted to update their facades. Esperdy argues that these updated storefronts served a range of complex purposes, such as stimulating public consumption, extending the New Deal’s influence, reviving a stagnant construction industry, and introducing European modernist design to the everyday landscape. She goes on to show that these diverse roles are inseparable, woven together not only by the crisis of the Depression, but also by the pressures of bourgeoning consumerism. As the decade’s two major cultural forces, Esperdy concludes, consumerism and the Depression transformed the storefront from a seemingly insignificant element of the built environment into a potent site for the physical and rhetorical staging of recovery and progress.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aCommercial buildingszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aConsumption (Economics)zUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aNew Deal, 1933-1939. 0aStorefrontszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226218021423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226218021.jpg  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles